### Array Methods in C#

The `Array` class provides static methods for working with arrays.

### Sorting and Reversing

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 3, 1, 4, 1, 5 };
Array.Sort(numbers);      // { 1, 1, 3, 4, 5 }
Array.Reverse(numbers);   // { 5, 4, 3, 1, 1 }
```

### Searching

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `Array.IndexOf()` | Returns first index of value | `Array.IndexOf(arr, 5)` |
| `Array.LastIndexOf()` | Returns last index of value | `Array.LastIndexOf(arr, 5)` |
| `Array.BinarySearch()` | Binary search on sorted array | `Array.BinarySearch(arr, 5)` |
| `Array.Exists()` | Checks if element exists | `Array.Exists(arr, x => x > 5)` |
| `Array.Find()` | Finds first matching element | `Array.Find(arr, x => x > 3)` |
| `Array.FindAll()` | Finds all matching elements | `Array.FindAll(arr, x => x > 3)` |

### Resizing and Copying

```csharp
int[] arr = { 1, 2, 3 };
Array.Resize(ref arr, 5);  // Resize to 5 elements, new are 0

int[] copy = new int[3];
Array.Copy(arr, copy, 3);  // Copy elements

int[] clone = (int[])arr.Clone();  // Shallow clone
```

### Converting

```csharp
string[] words = { "1", "2", "3" };
int[] numbers = Array.ConvertAll(words, int.Parse);
```

### Clearing

```csharp
int[] arr = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
Array.Clear(arr, 0, arr.Length);  // All elements set to 0/null
```

### Array.ForEach

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
Array.ForEach(numbers, n => Console.WriteLine(n * 2));
```

### LINQ with Arrays

Arrays support LINQ extension methods:

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 };
int[] evens = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0).ToArray();
int[] squared = numbers.Select(n => n * n).ToArray();
int sum = numbers.Sum();
double avg = numbers.Average();
int max = numbers.Max();
int min = numbers.Min();
```

> **Key Point:** Array.Sort sorts in place (modifies the original array). Array.IndexOf returns -1 if not found. Array.Resize creates a new array and copies elements. For complex operations, consider using List<T> instead of arrays.

### Common Pattern: Find Maximum

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 3, 7, 2, 9, 4 };
int max = numbers.Max();  // Using LINQ
// Or manually:
int maxVal = numbers[0];
foreach (var n in numbers) if (n > maxVal) maxVal = n;

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int[] numbers = { 5, 2, 8, 1, 9, 3 };

        Console.WriteLine("Original: " + string.Join(", ", numbers));

        Array.Sort(numbers);
        Console.WriteLine("Sorted: " + string.Join(", ", numbers));

        Array.Reverse(numbers);
        Console.WriteLine("Reversed: " + string.Join(", ", numbers));

        Console.WriteLine($"Index of 5: {Array.IndexOf(numbers, 5)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Max: {numbers.Max()}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Sum: {numbers.Sum()}");
    }
}
